This paper is about object detection in images using region-based proposals. The paper discusses a new approach called "visual chunking" that iteratively selects from a set of arbitrarily shaped candidate regions to detect objects in an image. This approach involves designing an optimization criterion for measuring the performance of a list of detections and developing learning approaches to emulate the algorithm's behavior. Given the focus on computer vision and machine learning techniques, the most likely arXiv CS sub-categories are computer vision (cs.CV), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), and machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also discusses natural language processing techniques for evaluating the performance of the algorithm, which suggests that it could also be relevant to the computational linguistics (cs.CL) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses benchmark datasets for evaluating the algorithm's performance, which suggests that it could also be relevant to the multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category.
